<DOC><DOCNO> AP881210-0138 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-10-88 2055EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-North-Nir     12-10 0161</FIRST><SECOND>AM-North-Nir,150</SECOND><HEAD>Report: Two Planned To Acquire Soviet Tank</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former national security aide Oliver North andthe late Amiram Nir had planned to acquire a highly sophisticatedSoviet tank in Syria and have it shipped to the United States, apublished report said Saturday.   U.S. News andamp; World Report, quoting unnamed intelligence sourcesand referring to North's still secret notebooks, called for Israelto send an Arabic speaking arms expert with a fake Syrian passportinto that country with the help of ``unnamed Polish confederates.''   The goal of the expedition was an advanced version of the SovietUnion's T-72 high-tech battle tank, the magazine said in its``Washington Whispers'' column. The plan, in which the tank would beshipped to the United States ``via a circuitous route,'' was abortedbecause of disclosure of the Iran-Contra affair in November 1986,the magazine said.   Nir, a former Israeli counterterrorism official, died Nov. 30 ina plane crash in Mexico.</TEXT></DOC>